column1: How many people will have been fully vaccinated against COVID-19 in the US as of 31 May 2021, according to the CDC?
column5: ['Fewer than 120,000,000', 'Between 120,000,000 and 130,000,000, inclusive', 'More than 130,000,000 but fewer than 140,000,000', 'Between 140,000,000 and 150,000,000, inclusive', 'More than 150,000,000 but fewer than 160,000,000', 'Between 160,000,000 and 170,000,000, inclusive', 'More than 170,000,000']
column6: ['Technology', 'Society', 'Health']

Catching up with my failure to decrement daily! Bin D will only be achieved if the CDC makes major revisions to its late May data between now and the question's resolution on 14 June. I'm allowing a 10% chance for that to happen.

As of May 24, 132.5 million total and 7-day average has plummeted to 792k per day. 7 remaining days x 792k per day = 5.6 million. As of May 31, would have 138.12 million PER STRAIGHT LINE PROJECTION. Usingthe simple calculation above, this total has dropped continuously since the first forecast and is getting closer and close to the line between bins C and D.
This one's settled.
130.5M as of 5/21 with 10 days left. On a "peak" day we had 938,000 people vaccinated with 7-day average being about 8% lower than the required 950,000 to hit 140M by 5/31.

My rationale for updating so harshly was (besides prodding to pay attention) a review of all the 10 million vaccine jumps in the past. if you look at the cdc graph that serves as a resolution criteria, the number of days per 10m has been increasing, that ...coupled with the willingness saturation leads me to think that we will not be able to get over 140 m in the next few days

As of May 21, 130.5 million total and 7-day average has plummeted to 874k per day. 10 remaining days x 874k per day = 8.74 million. As of May 31, would have 139.24 million PER STRAIGHT LINE PROJECTION. Usingthe simple calculation above, this total has dropped continuously since the first forecast and is getting closer and close to the line between bins C and D. This will be a squeaker.

On reconsideration of today's forecast and review of good commentary by the handful of others providing rationales for their updates, I think it's time to move more aggressively toward Bin D given the limited remaining time.

Continuing my countdown to 0% on Bin D. It's still possible that late revisions by the CDC will get the end-of-May numbers over the 140M line, but that's decreasingly likely as the light-blue figures representing what the CDC perceives to be relatively solid numbers continue to be below 1M daily.
The daily grwoth is leveling off, so it probably won't hit the 140M
131.9m plus 1.5m backlog = 133.4m 5 reporting days to go Threshold for 140m = 6.6m or over 1m per day Current rate 900k per day and dropping.

Average of 0.95M/day added in the past week through May 25. This number has fallen from 1.47M over the past 3 weeks or so. 6 more days left in forecast (after May 25) + 3 for back reporting. 131.1M (total as of 5/25) + 0.95M/day * 9 days = 139.6M. So, even if the rate at which people are added doesn't continue to decline, we'll be under 140M. But we can expect the decline to continue through May 31; second doses for age 12 to 15 don't start until June. Moreover, it's reasonable to expect that fewer people will be vaccinated over the Memorial Day weekend. (And, there's no chance the numbers will be <130M.) Afternoon update: An average of 0.91M/day were added in the past week through May 26.

As of May 20, 129.4 million total and 7-day average has plummeted to 908k per day. 11 remaining days x 908k per day = 9.99 million. As of May 31, would have 139.4 million PER STRAIGHT LINE PROJECTION. Usingthe simple calculation above, this total has dropped continuously since the first forecast and is getting closer and close to the line between bins C and D. This will be a squeaker.

Continuing my move to Bin C as each day passes below the 1M daily level. Incremental daily shifts will accelerate once reporting for the past weekend solidifies (assuming the retrospective daily average stays below 1M).
based on current trend

I am finding the reporting on this less than reliable/ consistent. There is no way we are having the same amount of vaccines for multiple days in a row. "If" they are correct, then we will barely hit 131,000,000 by resolution date.

Average of 1.0M/day added in the past week (through May 23). As of 4 days ago, 1.11M/day had been added in past week. 1.47M/day in the previous week. 8 more days left in forecast (after May 23) + 3 for back reporting. 130.0M on 5/23 + 1.0M*11 = 141.0M. The number of people receiving a second dose continues to decline and probably won't go up at all until teenagers start receiving their second doses. All we need to see is the average number added/day to fall under 0.91M for the next 11 days for the final number to fall under 140M. That seems extremely likely, especially with the Memorial Day weekend coming up. I think it's very likely that far fewer people will get vaccinated over the Memorial Day weekend.

130M bin is approaching escape velocity. However, even though the tendency to fall is greater, there is still more room for a fall to still arrive at the 130 bin. It only takes an unexpected leveling off to leap this into the 140 bin.

Shifting more to Bin C (fewer than 140M) largely in response to good links from @Chrisp re continuing woes for the 1-shot J&J vaccine. New contamination reports re the Baltimore facility will only enhance the already formidable reluctance of Americans to get this vaccine. Without a viable one-shot option, I have a hard time seeing the average daily rate of new fully vaccinated people getting back over 1M for the remainder of May, which is what we need to see to get into Bin D.
The rate is slowing, but I want to see the weekend numbers, especially for children before I begin to really change my thinking.
current daily trends make it more likely we will end May under 140k.
Updating based on 5/23/21 numbers from https://ourworldindata.org/covid-vaccinations?country=USA -- reaching 130M but seeing slight decrease in average number of fully vaccinated per day.

As of May 18, 127.44 million total and growing by 987k million per day, per 7-day average. 13 remaining days x 987k per day = 12.83 million. As of May 31, would have 140.27 million PER STRAIGHT LINE PROJECTION. Usingthe simple calculation above, this total has dropped continuously since the first forecast and is getting closer and close to the line between bins C and D. This will be a squeaker.
129,066,466 as of 22 May. We need a daily rate of 1.215 mln from now on to get to 140 mln. The graph doesn't seem to suggest that rate.

As of May 17, 126.32 million total and growing by 1.023 million per day, per 7-day average. 14 remaining days x 1.023 million per day = 14.322 million. As of May 31, would have 140.64 million PER STRAIGHT LINE PROJECTION.

Slight increase because of crowd but watching out because there's a rise in first dose counts. But I don't think correlation is too strong here based on the graph. Have to give it one or two more days to see whether or not there is a continued decline. Unwise to go higher until this is observed.

As of May 16, 125.35 million total and growing by 1.043 million per day, per 7-day average. 14 remaining days x 1.043 million per day = 14.6 million. As of May 31, would have 139.9 million PER STRAIGHT LINE PROJECTION. Just two days ago that same math yielded 141.4 million.
Rate is down, and holiday weekend approaching.

Reversing my forecast substantially to 60/40 between bins C and D because the 7-day moving daily average of new fully vaccinated people has dropped more precipitously than I had expected. It's already down close to 1M per day, indicating that the new incentives and initiatives to make it easier for people to get vaccinated are not overcoming the barriers to converting those with a first dose into fully vaccinated individuals. I expect that daily average of new fully vaccinated individuals to begin rising again as the 12-15 year-old group starts to hit full vaccination, but that uptick will be too little, too late to make a meaningful difference to the May numbers.

The actual value, assuming 549K full vaccinations per day, will be 126 Million + 6 Million = 132 Million. If the number continues to decrease, it will be very close to 130 Million, straddling the 120M-130M and 130M-140M buckets.
People Vaccinated At Least One Dose Fully Vaccinated Total 160,177,820 126,605,166 to date May 20, 2021

The lowest point in the 7-day average since February was 1,421,139/day*. The highest point was 11 April, at 3,305,574. It’s been on a downward trend since then. Total is 126,605,169 fully vaccinated, with 11 days to go. At 3.3mn/day, it would be 162,905,169 (Bin F). No chance of that. At 2mn/day, it would be 148,605,169 (Bin D). At today’s 1.6mn/day*, it would be 144,205,169 (Bin D). At 1.4mn/day, it would be 142,005,169 (Bin D). At 1.2mn/day, it would be 139,805,169 (Bin C—but on the border with Bin D).

Average of 1.11M/day added in past week. 12 more days left in forecast + 3 for back reporting. 125.45M today + 1.11M*15 = 142.2M. But, in the week before, 1.47M/day were added, for a difference of 0.36M/day or 2.52M/week. If this decline continues, we'll see fewer than 140M fully vaccinated and perhaps closer to 138M. All we need to see is the average number added/day to fall under 0.97M for the next 15 days for the final number to fall under 140M. That seems extremely likely.

As of May 14, 123.7 million total and growing by 1.04 million per day, per 7-day average. 176 remaining days x 1.04 million per day = 17.7 million. As of May 31, would have 141.4 million PER STRAIGHT LINE PROJECTION. Just three days ago that same math yielded 144 million.

The average linear rate only needs to drop by approx 3% to fall one bin down, which seems reasonable and I deem the likely scenario. I guess I could be wrong if the new reopenings further pushes people to get vaccinated. However, I think this hypothesis wouldn't make a big difference because when restrictions are in place, that also encourages people to get vaccinated. They cancel each other out.
Quick update since my 5/12/20 prediction. Numbers dropping faster than expected and it will be closer than I had previously estimated (and more close to my original thoughts).

124.5m plus 1.5m for backlog reporting = 126m 12days to go. 140m threshold = 1.1m per day. Average just above, but is dropping quite fast. Will be close. Oops shouldn’t have swung so hard to over 140m on last forecast
My forecast is close to the line, but >140M.
Wow, reading the forecasting bars is tough!!!

Tiny tweak for passage of time and review of more recent data, as well as other forecasters' comments. I still see Bin D as the overwhelming favorite, but have swapped my 1% upside hedge on Bin E to increase my downside hedge on Bin C up to 3% (formerly 2%).

Into the fray, noting in the CDC data I just reviewed that there must be a reporting glitch as there has been no increase (0) in the last day or so, but I know a few people who had shot 2 over the weekend. Stay frosty my friends!

As of May 11, 120 million total and growing by 1.2 million per day, per 7-day average. 20 remaining days x 1.2 million per day = 24 million. As of May 31, would have 144 million PER STRAIGHT LINE PROJECTION.

Current pacing suggest that achieving 140m by end of May as highest probability - we stand at 121m today (may 17). In April there were almost 25m vaccinated in the back half of the month. Vax rates are slowing so May perhaps won't yield the same but reaching 130 looks clearly in sight
Assuming vacc Rate of 1m per day
Does anyone have figures for how reporting for individual days updates over time? At what point does data for an individual day remain stable?

As of May 12th, the number of fully vaccinated people in the US is at 119M with 331M receiving at least one dose (https://ourworldindata.org/covid-vaccinations?country=USA). The average daily rate is 2.09M vaccines—rolling 7-day average, single dose, and may not equal the total number of people vaccinated, depending on the specific dose regime. (https://ourworldindata.org/grapher/daily-covid-19-vaccination-doses). The average daily rate of new individuals fully vaccinated individuals is 1.345 from April 25-May 12 (https://ourworldindata.org/grapher/people-fully-vaccinated-covid?tab=chart&country=~USA).
at the current 7d average, we are on pace for about 145m fully vaccinated, but we are still seeing a general downward trend in the # of fully vaccinated.
119m plus 1.5m backlog = 120.5m 17 days to go 19.5m to get to 140m which is 1.15m per day Average is still 1.3m so most likely to get beyond 140m.
Someone thankfully pointed out how much the data can shift with the estimated information because my last estimate showed a 1,282,773 7-day average on 5/1. That number has been updated to 1,344,713.
116.6m plus 2m for backlog = 118.6m Threshold for 140m in 19 days needs 21.4m @1.12m per day Current rate still 1.3m.

CDC data show that nearly 114M people were fully vaccinated as of 6 May, the last day of this forecast for which they do not shade the data as being likely to be revised. As of the same date, a little over 152M had received at least one dose. This figure, plus any one-dose J&J vaccinations occurring through the remainder of May, represents something close to the theoretical maximum of people who could be fully vaccinated by the end of the month, given the minimum three-week lag between 1st & 2nd doses for Pfizer & Moderna. With the J&J vaccine just coming off the recommended pause and the obvious hesitancy of people to resume taking that vaccine, it seems nearly impossible for the # of fully vaccinated to exceed 160M at the end of May.
114.3m today plus 2m for backlog reporting = 116.3m 21 days to go Threshold 130m = 650k per day 140m = 1.12m per day

Based on the 7-day average of number of people added to this category per day falling by 0.16M/day/week from 2 weeks ago to 1 week ago and extending this trend downward, we could end up almost exactly at 140.0M, too close to call. I should probably weight the lower category more than I am.
110.8m. Add 2m for backlog reporting = 112.8m 23 days to go 130m = 750k per day 140m = 1.18m per day.
Good assessment by @Skyreichel here: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1273977

Updating my numbers because I definitely ignored the fact that it has to be a daily average across the time period. We will probably see numbers below the 785,000 threshold to miss 130M vaccinated people, but the average across this time period is much more likely to be above that. Had it poorly weighted in my last forecast.

We have 25 days left, plus the updates on the most recent data. Current considerations are number of people with first dose already because we only have time for more Pfizer 2-dose vaccinations and the J&J single-dose fully vaccinated. We must also consider the number of people who are vaccine hesitant or will refuse a vaccine because this decreases your ability to get fully vaccinated people when these appointments are going unfilled.

Following on from yesterday, I think having read up on why vaccinations are dropping (links in comment on the one or more dose question) the rate will still keep dropping, but not as fast as 1st doses. As 1.3m is the threshold for 140m and this is the current rate, which is going to drop, then makes it less likely to get to 140m. But has to drop a long way to get to 130m. Moving forecast more to this 130-140m range.
Expect the rate to slow down, as the Summer weather takes the wind out of the virus, and the media moves on to Riot season.

@Ryan-Beck makes the astute observation that people who get one dose of vaccine usually end up getting their second dose within a month. (It was a little under a month in March, but almost exactly 30 days right now.) I also agree with him that the J&J vaccine isn't moving much, and that its effects are likely to be pretty negligible on the forecast total.
107.3m today. 25 days to go. Thresholds: 120m = 500k per day 130m = 900k per day 140m = 1,3m per day 150m = 1,7m per day.

147 million first doses currently. After the 21 to 28 day window that should be the number of people who have their second dose, plus some delay. That held up pretty well last month too. So I'm centering in the 140s with some chance it hits lower or higher. J&J vaccinations have become basically negligible now unfortunately, so I'm not putting much weight on the possibility of J&J vaccinations boosting the fully vaccinated numbers higher.
Wrong bin.
